      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen we are born, we cannot walk and must be carried in our parents' arms. Over time, we begin to crawl, take our first steps, and eventually learn to run. The process of learning follows a similar progression: we start with the basics and, gradually, move on to more complex concepts. In this text, we will explore the first steps of this journey in both reading and *pre-mathematics*, focusing on addition",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d6a6b284-a060-4a85-bc6c-9d2fe442254c",
                     "text": "González Redondo, Francisco A.",
                     "page": "00:08:20",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_road",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Roads\n\nFigure 1 depicts a section of the archaeological site of Teotihuacan in Mexico",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"ChronologyTeotihuacan\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('ChronologyTeotihuacan', '0%')\" src=\"images/Teotihuacan/TeotihuacanGeneral.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 1: General view of Teotihuacan. Photograph taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "General view of Teotihuacan city. In this photo it is possible to observe different constructions in format Talud-Tablero, and in the background we have pyramidal structures representing sacred moutains.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The indigenous peoples of the Americas (*Abya Yala*) not only built roads within their cities but also developed extensive networks connecting different regions. For example, the Mayas constructed **sacbes** (plural: **sacbeob**), which were white roads designed to simplify movement between cities",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "19ea1063-0ddd-4468-ad3e-2635675ca68d",
                     "text": "LaRocque, A., Leblon, B., Ek, J., and Folan, W. J.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "In the southern part of the continent, the Incas created an impressive network of routes spanning 39,000 kilometers, known as the **Qhapaq Ñan**, which linked diverse regions. Portions of these routes were originally built by earlier civilizations, such as the Wari",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0bc6455e-7fdb-49cd-bf29-c3675aca4d4f",
                     "text": "Jurado, L. R. C. V.",
                     "page": "pp. 1270 - 1271",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On Roads</b><br /><br />Roads are not exclusive to the indigenous peoples of the Americas (<i>Abya Yala</i>). Even today, we continue to build streets, highways, and routes that serve similar purposes—facilitating movement and connection between cities.<br /><br />Additionally, rivers, which follow natural courses, have been and continue to be used as pathways by various cultures around the world.<br /><br />Can you identify any connections between texts and roads?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_alphabet",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The vowels\n\nThe learning of any subject is based in the previous knowledgement. When children begin to study, the child is the main personage in his new discovery, including the reading process",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b5b8ecc8-037a-4d96-93de-4c2f1953d444",
                     "text": "Martins, Margarida Alves, and Ana Cristina Silva",
                     "page": "pp. 50",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1999",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "The process of spell words happen in different steps. The voewels, for example, are simpler to use, because they have the same sound associaed with the value we write. In the Latin alphabet, the vowel names (a, e, i, o, u) also have the same sound we spell them",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "8a876eef-1550-488a-90fc-e5a8eec14d41",
                     "text": "Dicionário da Língua Portuguesa",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b5b8ecc8-037a-4d96-93de-4c2f1953d444",
                     "text": "Martins, Margarida Alves, and Ana Cristina Silva",
                     "page": "pp. 54",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1999",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "5c2b00ac-9609-4102-9bfb-a688b092bad6",
                     "text": "Real Academia Española y Asociación de Academias de la Lengua Española",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "6fe155f8-e95f-42b4-9b14-df20e63e1847",
                     "text": "Herraiz, Elena",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1: Pronunciation and writting</b><br />Spell loud the vowels, one by one. After this, write them in continuation:<br /><br />A&nbsp; E&nbsp; I&nbsp; O&nbsp; U&nbsp;<br /><br />__ __ __ __ __</div></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_building",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Forming Words\n\nThe process of forming a word goes beyond simply writing letters next to each other. These letters, when combined, must convey meaning and provide information that is understandable to others. An example of such words are interjections, which express emotions",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "88726a34-89f2-45e8-baae-befa3e1d4c0b",
                     "text": "Dicionário da Língua Portuguesa",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul> <li><b>Attention or alert:</b> Oi!</li> <li><b>Disgust:</b> Ee!</li> <li><b>Joy:</b> Io!</li> </ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "There are many other interjections we use on a daily basis, but here we will focus only on interjections that use vowels, building knowledge step by step. As you can observe, when we pronounce these words (interjections), the vowel sounds are preserved, even when they are combined with other vowels.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_math",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction to Maths in Words\n\nEverything we have seen in this text has a direct relationship with maths. For example, writing a single vowel (a letter) is like writing a unique number between 0 and 9. Both have a unique representation. Similarly, when we write numbers side by side, we create a new number, just as we do when we combine letters to form words",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: On Sums</b><br /><br />If we can draw an analogy between letters and numbers, can we also say that we \"add\" letters to create a new word?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Although we might think that the interjection \"Oi\" is the sum of the vowels \"O\" and \"I,\" this idea would be imprecise. This is because, if we were to \"sum\" two letters, the result would need to exceed the last letter of the alphabet, \"Z,\" and loop back to \"O,\" exceeding \"I\".\n\nOn the other hand, we can associate reading words with walking a path, similar to an axis on which we position numbers",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0713ca05-8889-427b-802e-f2d31f045c09",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Walking Among Numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Conclusion\n\nIn this text, we explored the connection between words and mathematics. Based on what was presented in *Walking among numbers*, we saw that it is still not possible to establish a direct link between the formation of words and the addition operation. However, as we deepen our understanding of mathematical concepts, we will revisit this topic to further enhance our knowledge of the subject",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0713ca05-8889-427b-802e-f2d31f045c09",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Walking Among Numbers",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
